The paper focuses on developing a data-driven approach to numerically characterize the operative difficulty demand of complex teleoperation in robot-assisted systems. This involves leveraging user physiological and kinematic response data to predict task difficulty, which suggests a focus on human-robot interaction (cs.HC) and machine learning (cs.LG, cs.CV, cs.AI) techniques. Additionally, the paper specifically applies this approach to teleoperated robotic needle steering, which falls under the category of robotics (cs.RO).
